							<div align=left id="content-works">
							
							<h2>Journey Home</h2>
							<p><b>Voicing:</b> SATB chorus, soprano descant, Piano</p>
							<p><b>Text:</b> Erik Halvorson, adapted by the composer</p>
							<p><b>Language:</b> English & Spanish</p>
							<p><b>Duration:</b> 4 min.</p>
							<p><b>Commissioned</b> by the Minnesota Chorale, Kathy Saltzman Romey, Artistic Director, and premiered as part of the <em>Bridges 2007: Sing Me a Home</em> concert, with support from the National Endowment for the Arts and the Target Foundation.</p>
							<p><b>Premiere:</b> May 19, 2007; Choir of Como Park High School; Carole Whitney, cond.</p>
							<p><b>Published:</b> Santa Barbara Music Pub. Jo-Michael Scheibe Choral Series #865</p>
							<p><b>See the score:</b> <a href="http://sbmp.com/PerusalFiles/SBMP865.pdf" target="_blank">PREVIEW THE FULL SCORE (download PDF)</a></p>
							<br>
							<iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/C44nc-lIrsE" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe><br>
							<span class="text-small">Performed by 900 California students at the 26th Annual High School Choir Festival at Walt Disney Concert Hall - Grant Gershon, conductor.</span><br>
							<br>
							Audio of "Journey Home": <i><a href="../sound/betinis--journey_home.mp3" target="_blank">mp3, 4:11, 4 MB</a></i><br>
							<span class="resume-small">Performed live by the Chamber Choir at the Missota Music Festival - Kathy Romey, conductor.</span><br>
							<br>
							</div>
							<hr>
							<span class="works-headers">PROGRAMMING THEMES:</span>
								<div class="works-body">
								<em>immigration, refugee experience, home, international relations, global community, multi-culturalism, travel, Mexican-American experience, building dedication, housing, Habitat for Humanity, love, family</em>
								</div>
							<br>
							<span class="works-headers">PUBLISHER'S SUMMARY:</span>
								<div class="works-body">
								This commissioned piece, supported by the National Endowment for the Arts, explores the emotional feelings of immigrants who find a new home and life in the United States. Composer Betinis artistically, and dramatically brings the text to life.  -Santa Barbara Music Publishing
								</div>
							<br>
							<span class="works-headers">PRACTICE TRACKS (click to play, right-click to download):</span>
								<div class="works-body">
								<strong>Piano only</strong> (quarter = 108): <a href="../sound/journey_home--piano--at_108.mp3" target="blank">journey_home--piano--at_108.mp3</a><br>
								<strong>Full score</strong> (quarter = 108): <a href="../sound/journey_home--full--at_108.mp3" target="blank">journey_home--full--at_108.mp3</a><br>
								</div>
							<br>
							<span class="works-headers">ABBIE'S PROGRAM NOTE:</span>
							<div class="works-body">
							This piece was commissioned by the Minnesota Chorale as part of an amazing and innovative series called "<a href="http://www.mnchorale.org/past_bridges.htm" target="blank">Bridges</a>."  In 2007, they partnered with Habitat for Humanity to create a concert called "Sing Me a Home."  They commissioned five composers to work directly with high school lyricists on a new piece celebrating specific Habitat for Humanity families in their school. I worked with poet Erik Halverson (then a student at Como Park High School) to develop this text about a family who emigrated from Mexico to Erik's school in Saint Paul, Minnesota.<br>
							<br>
							One of the greatest joys for me about this piece's premiere was meeting the family who inspired it.  Sitting next to me in the church pews, the Mexican family's 3-year-old son clutched a small photo album documenting the building of his house, and though he didn't say a word, grinned at me and silently pointed to himself in every picture... as if saying "I was there!"  Such joy, such pride.<br>
							<br>
							Another unique aspect of this commission was the opportunity to create a lead sheet of the piece for free community use.  The lead sheet has a Creative Commons copyright, which means you may print and disperse this file as you like, as long as you don't sell it.<br>
							<br>
							<a href="../pdfs/betinis--journey_home_leadsheet.pdf" target="blank">To view or download the free lead sheet, click here.</a><br>
							</div>
							<br>
							<span class="works-headers">TEXT for "Journey Home":</span>
								<div class="works-body">
									<div id="poem">
									<span class="text-small">by Erik Halvorson (edited and adapted by Abbie Betinis, Chad Zdroik and Gabrielle Diharce)</span><br>
									<br>
									<center>
									<table>
										<tr>
											<td>
											<span id="poem_title"><strong>Spoken (in Spanish):</strong></span><br>
											Un lugar... un hogar...  <em>nuestro</em> hogar.<br>
											Un lugar que podemos llamar el nuestro, hacer el nuestro.<br>
											Un lugar para vivir, crecer, y ser.<br>
											Un pedazo de lo nuestro que compartimos con el mundo.<br>
											Un trozo de nuestros corazónes que traemos a la comunidad.<br>
											Un mundo de consuelo, y un mundo de calma.<br>
											Un mundo... de amor.<br>								
											</td>
											
											<td>
											<span id="poem_title"><em>English Translation:</em></span><br>
											<em>A place... a home... <strong>our</strong> home.<br>
											A place we can call our own, make our own.<br>
											A place to live, grow, and be.<br>
											A piece of us we share with the world.<br>
											A piece of our hearts we bring to the community.<br>
											A world of comfort, and a world of calm.<br>
											A world... of love.</em><br>
											</td>
										</tr>
									</table>
									</center>
								<br>
									<center>
									<table>
										<tr>
											<td>
											
								<strong>Sung:</strong><br>
								A place, a place to live,<br>
								a place to grow,<br>
								and be.<br>
								<br>
								A place, a place to hope,<br>
								a place to dream,<br>
								and love...<br>
								<br>
								An end, an end to a journey,<br>
								but still we're just beginning:<br>
								a place with you,<br>
								a place to start anew.<br>
								<br>
								A home,  <em>(Un hogar)</em><br>
								a home is our own, <em>(nuestro propia hogar)</em><br>
								yet so much more,  <em>(y mucho más)</em><br>
								a world... <em>(un mundo)</em><br>
								<br>
								A world,  <em>(Un mundo)</em><br>
								a world we'll learn, <em>(aprenderemos)</em><br>
								a world we'll bring,  <em>(lo traeremos)</em><br>
								and share... <em>(para compartir)</em><br>
								<br>
								A world of comfort, of calm,<br>
								the hope of our family,<br>
								a place of love, <br>
								of wonder from above...<br>
								<br>
								A place, a place we'll grow,<br>
								a place we'll learn,<br>
								and share.<br>
								<br>
								A place to call our own,<br>
								to make our own...<br>
								<br>
								Our home.<br>
								<br> 
											</td>
										</tr>
									</table>
									</center>
					       <span id="poem_credit"><hr width="10%" align="left">Used by permission of Erik Halvorson and Santa Barbara Music Publishing, Inc.  Spanish translation by Chad Zdroik and Gabrielle Diharce.  This poem may be reprinted from this website ONLY for use in concert programs and for promotional use as related to this musical work.</span>  
							</div>
						</div>
